P, Proline and Hydroxyproline The geometry selected for' proline (with the pyrrolidine ring
in the up, down, and planar conformations, where these terms refer to the relative positions of the CY and CB atoms; see Fig. ISA, 8, C) are given in Table VII. Because of this possible puckering of the pyrrolidine ring, three different geometries are described in Table VII, and the corresponding dihedral angles are given in Table VIII. The data of Table VII conform as closely as possible to reliable x-ray and neutron diffraction data.131-168 The dihedral angles of Table VIII were obtained by varying , 1, 2, 3, and 6 (keeping bond lengths and bond angles fixed) to obtain exact ring closure. It should be noted that, in the two resulting puckered conformations of the pyrrolidine ring, the position of the CY atom is determined by and 1 (positive values of x1 pertain to a clockwise rotation of the CY atom when looking from C8 to CS). The two puckered conformations

are designated up (U) and down (D), with · -67.6°, 1 = -6.11° (for U) and - -75.0°, x1 +18.67° (for D); these values of and 1 pertain to both the cis and trans conformations about the X-Pro bond. It can be seen in Fig. 15A end B that, in both the

U and D forms, both the CB and CY atoms lie out of the plane

defined by the Ca, N and C® atoms,

Besides these differences In the puckering of the pyrrolidine

ring, there is also a different bond length for the X-Pro peptide

bond,161,165 viz., 1.36 A instead of 1.325 A. Further, in trans

tiC’j.^C^) X-Pro (Ul-1 - 180°), the bond angles161,165 are

