Appendix III. Algorithm for Directing the Formation of Disulfide Bonds

When disulfide bonds occur in a protein, it is necessary to direct the approach of the two half-cystine residues (re-
ferred to as t and j) so that the S-S bond length, the bond
angles t(C,sS¿S;) and t(S¡S7C/), and the dihedral angle C,'<iS;S;C/j(xs,s-') are close to the corresponding experimental values. Since bond lengths and bond angles are generally fixed in these calculations,60 a functional form for the loop-closing energy has been chosen so that its value goes to zero when the disulfide bond has been formed properly, i.e., when the calculated bond lengths and bond angles are the same as the values chosen from experiment [S/S,· bond length84,153 = 2.04 Á, t(C¿6S;S;) and t(S;S;'C/6) bond angles84,153 = 104°]. Another term is included in this algorithm to simulate the twofold potential for rotation about the SS bond (variation of xs,s'). Experimentally, this barrier has been reported73 to be approximately 7 kcal/mol with the maxima occurring at xs,sj = 0 and 180°, and minima at ±90°.
The disulfide-bond-forming algorithm is defined analyti-
cally by

U(xss) = A(r4 - r4,0)2

