J. J. Verbist, Mater. Res. Bull., 7, 1225 (1972). (34) One problem in adopting geometric parameters obtained from amino
acids, dipeptides, etc. is that most of these molecules exist in a ß structure in the crystals. If the geometry depends greatly on the conformation, this dependence would escape us since there are essentially no small to medium-sized molecules, for which precise crystal data exist, that are not ß structures. (35) An inconsistency in geometry has recently been brought to our attention, viz., the gas-phase structures of AAmethylacetamide36 and acetamide37 both have C'-N bond lengths (~1.38 Á) which are considerably larger than those (1.29 A in NMA and 1.334 A in acetamide) observed in crystals of these molecules.38"·*0 Since the other bond lengths and bond angles appear to be similar in the gas phase and In the crystal, this discrepancy in the peptide bond length will require further study. A possible resolution of this dilemma may lie in the recent work of F. K. Winkler and J. D. Dunitz (paper presented at the Penn State Meeting on Intermolecular Forces, Aug 1974). These workers
showed that protonation of the C'=0 oxygen of a peptide lengthens the C'-O bond and shortens the C'-N peptide bond, and that a peptide bond length of 1.32 A corresponds to about 15-20% protonation,
which could arise (in the crystal) from intermolecular hydrogen bond
formation. Since the C'=0 groups of polypeptides and proteins are
very often hydrogen bonded, it appears best to use the crystal rather than the gas-phase value for the peptide bond length. (36) M. Kitano, T. Fukuyama, and K. Kuchitsu, Bull. Chem. Soc. Jpn., 46,
